### Channels in Kotlin

Channels provide a way to transfer a stream of values between coroutines. They are like hot streams -- different from Flow which is cold.

---

### Channel Basics

```kotlin
import kotlinx.coroutines.channels.*
import kotlinx.coroutines.*

fun main() = runBlocking {
    val channel = Channel<Int>()

    launch {
        for (i in 1..5) {
            channel.send(i)
            delay(500)
        }
        channel.close()
    }

    for (value in channel) {
        println("Received: $value")
    }
}
```

---

### Channel Types

| Type | Capacity | Behavior |
|------|----------|----------|
| `Channel()` / `RendezvousChannel` | 0 | Sender waits until receiver is ready |
| `Channel(Channel.UNLIMITED)` | Unlimited | Never suspends on send |
| `Channel(Channel.CONFLATED)` | 1 | Keeps only the latest value |
| `Channel(capacity)` | N | Buffered channel |

---

### Buffered Channels

```kotlin
val channel = Channel<Int>(capacity = 10)

launch {
    repeat(20) {
        channel.send(it)
        println("Sent $it")
    }
    channel.close()
}

launch {
    for (item in channel) {
        delay(100)
        println("Got $item")
    }
}
```

---

### Closing Channels

```kotlin
val channel = Channel<Int>()

launch {
    channel.send(1)
    channel.send(2)
    channel.close()  // No more elements
}

// Safe iteration
for (value in channel) {
    println(value)
}
```

---

### Fan-Out

Multiple coroutines can receive from the same channel.

```kotlin
fun main() = runBlocking {
    val channel = Channel<Int>()

    repeat(3) { id ->
        launch {
            for (value in channel) {
                println("Consumer $id: $value")
                delay(100)
            }
        }
    }

    repeat(10) { channel.send(it) }
    channel.close()
}
```

---

### Fan-In

Multiple coroutines can send to the same channel.

```kotlin
fun main() = runBlocking {
    val channel = Channel<String>()

    launch {
        listOf("A", "B", "C").forEach { channel.send(it) }
    }
    launch {
        listOf("X", "Y", "Z").forEach { channel.send(it) }
    }

    repeat(6) {
        println(channel.receive())
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Channels are hot streams -- they exist independently of consumers. Use `flow` for cold async streams and `channel` for hot producer-consumer patterns.

codeExample:
import kotlinx.coroutines.*
import kotlinx.coroutines.channels.*

fun main() = runBlocking {
    val channel = Channel<Int>(Channel.CONFLATED)

    launch {
        repeat(10) {
            channel.send(it)
            println("Sent $it")
        }
        channel.close()
    }

    launch {
        for (value in channel) {
            println("Received: $value")
            delay(200)
        }
    }
}
